%I A394508 #19 Apr 11 2026 00:52:45
%S A394508 2,6,15,40,121,484,2589,18896,180243,2176090,32236017,571516348,
%T A394508 11885151423,285237145366,7794999370325,239867327549926,
%U A394508 8232788441242913,312611538663794774,13040004273788572963
%N A394508 Write the primes in a column. Add new columns to the right, with each entry being the prime whose index is the entry to its left. The sequence a(n) is given by the antidiagonal sums.
%C A394508 Conjecture: a(n) is composite for n>1.
%F A394508 a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} prime^(n-k+1)(k), where prime(m) denotes the m-th prime number and the superscript means functional iteration: prime^1(m) = prime(m), prime^2(m) = prime(prime(m)), prime^3(m) = prime(prime(prime(m))), etc.
%e A394508 The first four rows of the table are:
%e A394508   Row 1: 2, 3, 5, 11, ...
%e A394508   Row 2: 3, 5, 11, 31, ...
%e A394508   Row 3: 5, 11, 31, 127, ...
%e A394508   Row 4: 7, 17, 59, 277, ...
%e A394508 The sums of the antidiagonals are:
%e A394508   a(1) = 2.
%e A394508   a(2) = 3 + 3 = 6.
%e A394508   a(3) = 5 + 5 + 5 = 15.
%e A394508   a(4) = 7 + 11 + 11 + 11 = 40.
%Y A394508 Cf. A377173.
%Y A394508 Cf. A007097 (1st, 2nd, 3rd, ... row), A057450 (4th, 7th, ... row), A057451 (6th, 13th, ... row), A057452 (8th, ... row), A057453 (9th, ... row), A057456 (10th, ... row), A057457 (12th, ... row), A394678 (14th, ... row).
